args:
Jinlorda speaks about how Nedrick wants to
give power to all who lack it, and the prince is
flustered by his own lack of understanding.
Jinlorda then uses a new power he calls
apotheosis to take the form of the Flamewyrm
and attacks the prince.
Stand down, Jinlorda. As I said before,\nI have no quarrel with the Faerie Kingdom.

I cannot. So long as there remains even
the slightest possibility that you might
interfere with Nedrick, I cannot suffer
you to pass.
Even if it comes at the cost of my life.
You truly are a fascinating individual.

You are quick to seize any opportunity that
serves your ends—regardless of how it
might stain you—and possess a rationality
unswayed by emotion.
Yet now you make a completely irrational\ndecision to wager your life for Nedrick's.
Are you truly so devoted to the man?
Enough, Jinlorda. You said you would tell\nus what we wished to know if we bested\nyou, and we have done so. Now speak.
Indeed I did. And as promised, I will tell\nyou a truth about the beings you all know\nas faeries.
This will affect you most of all, Notte.\nI know you've felt your own lack of strength\nbefore, yes? Your own weakness?
I know you've had agonizing moments\nwhere you could have done something\namazing if only you were a little stronger...
Moments? Dude, it's ALWAYS like that!\nEverybody else gets to help each other,\nand I'm always just...watching.

Just so. Faeries are among the weakest
of all creatures, despite the fact we share
roots with the most powerful creatures in 
this or any world: dragons.
Oh wowzers. I'd heard dragons and faeries\nwere related somehow, but...
Not merely related, my dear Notte.\nOne could easily name us siblings.
Long, long ago, there was an era when\nthis world held no people, no dragons,\nand no faeries.
But then, faeries and dragons alike were\nbrought into being by the same creator.

And dragons are now a vital part of this
existence-one could even say they make
our world function. Am I mistaken in this,
Flamewyrm Brunhilda?
I can't deny it. The winds, rains, and\nbudding of the earth are all brought into\nbeing through dragonkind. But what of it?
You do not even see your own privilege.\nThis is an arrogance so very typical for\na dragon.
...You're good at getting on my nerves.\nAre you looking for a fight?
It is not my intent to provoke you.\nI am merely pointing out facts.
Okay, I've had about enough of this smug\nso-and-so. Get ready for a beatdown, bub!
Easy, Mym. Let him finish—provided he\ncan do so in a timely manner?
Then let me speak plain: Dragons and\nfaeries are siblings with the same parent,\nyet they differ vastly.
In contrast to the dragons who are a part of\nthis world, faeries have little choice but to\nhide themselves away in a corner of it.
All because we were created\nwithout power.
This is a grudge, then? You desire kind\ntreatment because you were born weak?
I am not merely speaking about faeries.\nMany in this world lack power.

Some come into this world weak. Some
are struck down by illness. And some
simply have the ill luck to be born into
unfortunate circumstances.
How many choices—TRUE choices—do you\nthink people in such situations have?
As the faerie king, I am grateful for the\ngood life Notte was afforded in the care of\n{player_name} and his family.
But suppose they were people of a crueler\nbent. How much agency over her life would\nNotte have held in that case?

Tell me, Notte. What if the royals put you
to work as a slave, or treated you as an
emotionless plaything? What would you
have done in such a case?
I don't know. But until I met Zethia,\nI was pretty dang miserable.

I slept out in the rain, I was always cold
and shivering, and I was convinced some
crazy thing was gonna eat me pretty much
every second of the day.
Do you see now? This is reality for us\nfaeries—as well as for all who exist\nwithout power in this world.

Their options for life are woefully lacking.
But would you name it a sin for them to
seek power? To seek an ability to make
real choices for themselves?

Nedrick was once so powerless. A cruel
disease took his life and forced him into
a warped pact with a dragon, so that even
now he cannot exist without mana.
All choice was stolen from him, which is\nwhy he knows so keenly the pain of the\npowerless—and their longing for change.
All he seeks is a way to make this world\none where those without agency might be\nable to obtain it.
And that is why I risk my life for his.
I understand your ideals, and even\nsympathize with them—but that does\nnot mean we can ignore your actions.

If the weak gain power, those who once
held sway will in turn become weak.
The situation will merely reverse itself;
nothing will change.
Spoken like the pathetic king of a fallen\nland. You remind me of my father.
You list all the reasons not to change and\nin doing so prize stagnation, without ever\nrealizing this road leads only to death.
It is clear this discussion can serve no\nfurther purpose—though I must say I\nfound portions of it enlightening.
For you see, my determination to stop you\nhas now become an unshakable rock deep\nwithin my very core.
Jinlorda, wait! I want to understand what\nyou're saying—I truly do. But I think I\nneed to talk to Nedrick first.
Will you let me do that? Will you help me\nto understand?
If Nedrick is a friend to the weak who\nseeks to wield his power justly, then he\nand I share the same goal.
And who are you to make that decision?!
You don't know the first thing about my\ndarling—or the rest of us, for that matter!
I know plenty. For example, I know you\nwould never permit me to seize even a\nmodicum of power for myself.
Actually, I don't give a crap what you do.
Oh? Then you would not mind if I seized\npower like...this?
What is... Wait, what's going on?\nThis is wrong... This is WRONG!
See me, my friends! See me very well!
WHY DOES HE LOOK LIKE ME?!
Is it not obvious? I have shapeshifted.
Don't be absurd! You can't shapeshift!\nYou have no pact!

Normally, you would be right. But this is
another kind of shapeshifting—a magic
discovered by Finlorda which uses mana
to change one's form.
Shapeshifting involves forging a pact in\norder to borrow mana, but with this power,\nthe borrowing needs no pact.
You bear witness to a new power:\nApotheosis!
Taking power without a contract is no\nmore than base thievery.
Thievery? You wound me! The power is not\nstolen, but borrowed—and I will return it\nas soon as I burn you to ash!
Oh, I haven't been this furious in SO long!\nYou dare take MY form and then turn fire\nupon MY darling?! You'll die for this!
...Sorry sister, but I'm furious, too.\nFurious at this puppet prince.
You say you want to understand Nedrick?\nYou think you CAN?

You who were born from the flesh of the
Other, given the power of shapeshifting,
and raised in life of wealth and privilege?
You think you can understand Nedrick?
Your words are an insult to him!
So I will grant the death you deserve,\ndelivered in the form of she who loves you!
